  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Relapse is the most serious problem in alcoholism treatment. The overall aim of the present
      study was to determine if a treatment directed at changing the patient's social network, from
      one that reinforces drinking behavior to one that reinforces sobriety, can create the
      conditions necessary for long-term treatment success. In addition, we intended to determine
      if explicit reinforcement for this change of social network (Contingency Management or ContM)
      would be more effective than the same network support intervention without contingent
      reinforcement for change.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
